<NOTE>For release Saturday, Oct. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, Oct. 1, the 275th day of 1988. There are 91
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1908, Henry Ford introduced the Model T to the market, at a
cost of $825 per car. (In his book ``Ford: The Men and the
Machine,'' Robert Lacey points out that in 1908, an average
teacher's annual salary was $850.) The Model T proved a huge
success; more than 15 million were sold before the line was
discontinued.
   On this date:
   In 1800, Spain ceded Louisiana to France in a secret treaty.
   In 1885, special delivery mail service began in the United
States.
   In 1903, the Pittsburgh Pirates defeated the home team Boston
Pilgrims (Red Sox), 7-3, in the first World Series game. Boston,
however, went on to win the series, five games to three.
   In 1936, Gen. Francisco Franco was proclaimed the head of an
insurgent Spanish state.
   In 1943, Allied forces captured Naples during World War II.
   In 1949, Communist Party Chairman Mao Tse-tung raised the first
flag of the People's Republic of China in a proclamation ceremony
in Peking.
   In 1961, Roger Maris hit his 61st home run during a 162-game
season, in comparison to Babe Ruth's 60 home runs during a 154-game
season.
   In 1962, Johnny Carson succeeded Jack Parr as permanent host of
NBC-TV's ``Tonight'' show. Carson's guests that night were Joan
Crawford, Mel Brooks, Rudy Vallee and Tony Bennett.
   In 1971, Walt Disney World opened in Orlando, Fla.
   In 1980, Soviet cosmonauts Valery Ryumin and Leonid Popov set a
world space endurance record as they spent their 176th day aboard
an orbiting Salyut space station.
   In 1982, West Germany's Parliament voted to oust Helmut Schmidt
as chancellor and replace him with Helmut Kohl _ the first time in
the federal republic's 33-year history that a chancellor was
removed by Parliament.
   In 1986, former President Jimmy Carter's new presidential
library and museum were dedicated in Atlanta with help from
President Reagan, who said he and his predecessor had come together
in ``mutual respect.''
   Ten years ago: U.S. and Soviet negotiators concluded talks in
Washington on a strategic arms accord, saying that while remaining
issues remained unresolved, progress had been made.
   Five years ago: Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale won a
straw poll at the Maine Democratic state convention in Augusta,
thereby protecting his lead in his party's presidential race.
   One year ago: At least six people were killed when an earthquake
measuring 6.1 on the Richter scale struck the Greater Los Angeles
area.
   Today's birthdays: Pianist Vladimir Horowitz is 83. Actor Walter
Matthau is 67. Actor James Whitmore is 66. Former President Jimmy
Carter is 63. William Rehnquist, chief justice of the United
States, is 63. Actor Tom Bosley is 60. Actor George Peppard is 59.
Actor Richard Harris is 54. Actress-singer Julie Andrews is 52.
Former baseball player Rod Carew is 42.
   Thought for today: ``History is bunk!'' _ Attributed to Henry
Ford.
</TEXT>
